<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUICIDE RISK FACTORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I find it to be very helpful when you write about risk factors for 
different diseases, such as diabetes. Have you ever done this for young people 
who may be suicidal? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Possible risk factors for suicide among the young include loss of a 
parent; family disruption, such as separation or divorce; emotional stress; a 
history of abuse, neglect, or both; having a family member or friend who 
committed suicide; previous suicide attempts; a history of alcohol or drug 
abuse or a family member with a history of drug dependency; and access to 
firearms. 
</P>
<P>
 Neil Solomon is the author of "Sick &amp; Tired of Being Sick &amp; Tired," 
Wynwood Press. If you have a medical question, write to Dr. Solomon, P.O. Box 
36184, Baltimore, Md. 21285-6184. Solomon cannot give personal replies but will 
answer as many questions as possible in his column. 
</P>
</TEXT>
