<HEADLINE>
<P>
BANNING LITTLE RED RIDING HOOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Little Red Riding Hood has been banned in Culver City first-grade classrooms 
because some parents claimed that Trina Schart Hyman's version of the Brothers 
Grimm fairy tale promotes alcoholism among primary students (Metro, May 19). 
</P>
<P>
In this version Little Red takes a loaf of fresh bread, some sweet butter, and 
a bottle of wine to her grandmother's cottage in the deep woods. After being 
eaten by the wolf, Granny and Red are rescued by a huntsman. They celebrate by 
eating the fresh bread and sweet butter. "Grandmother drank some of the wine 
and Red Riding Hood had a cup of blackberry tea. After a while, grandmother 
felt quite strong and healthy." The illustration shows grandmother flushed and 
cheerful with a glass of wine in her hand. This critics say sends a message to 
first graders that drinking wine is an acceptable way to relieve stress and 
feel better. 
</P>
<P>
Nonsense. First graders know the best way to relieve stress is to throw 
tantrums, hit younger siblings and break toys. They prefer French fries, soda 
pop and sugared cereal to wine. 
</P>
<P>
If parents want to complain, how about cruelty to animals? The huntsman cuts 
open the wolf while the animal is snoozing in grandma's bed. Isn't that cause 
for animal rights' activists to protest this story? The huntsman also skins the 
wolf and takes the pelt. Where are the groups against fur coats? 
</P>
<P>
This version of Little Red Riding Hood won national awards and is included on 
the recommended reading list published by the California State Department of 
Education. Yet some nit-pickers begrudge poor, old, ailing granny a glass of 
wine. 
</P>
<P>
Why do some adults read things into fairy tales? What child considers 
Goldilocks and the Three Bears a personal rights case or the Little Red Hen a 
worker's compensation case? "Oh, A Hunting We Will Go" use to be a children's 
song. Now it seems to be a book banner's anthem. 
</P>
<P>
MARJORIE MILLER 
</P>
<P>
Hesperia 
</P>
</TEXT>
